[[Buran (spacecraft)|Buran]], the Russian equivalent to the Space Shuttle, is destroyed in a storm at [[Baikonur Cosmodrome|Baikonur]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/1985631.stm|title=Russia's space dreams abandoned|date=2002-05-13|access-date=2019-10-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*[[May 20]] &ndash; [[East Timor]] regains its independence after 2-and-a-half years of United Nations administration and 26 years of [[Indonesian occupation of East Timor|occupation]] by [[Indonesia]] since [[1975]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/05/19/1021801638341.html|title=East Timor celebrates as a nation is born|last=|first=|date=2002-05-20|website=The Age|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref>\n* [[May 24]] &ndash; In Moscow, United States President [[George W. Bush]] and Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] sign the [[Strategic Offensive Reductions Treaty]] to replace the [[Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty]] of [[1972]] and the [[START II|START II Treaty]] of [[1993]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/europe/05/24/bush.europe/|title=Bush, Putin sign arms deal|last=|first=|date=2002-05-24|website=CNN|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref>\n* [[May 25]] &ndash; A [[Boeing 747]] operating as [[China Airlines Flight 611]] breaks up and crashes in the [[Taiwan Strait]], killing all 225 passengers and crew on board.\n* [[May 31]] &ndash; [[June 30]] &ndash; The [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] in South Korea and Japan;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/may/31/worldcupfootball2002.sport10|title=The opening ceremony: as it happened|last=Murray|first=Scott|date=2002-05-31|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref> which is ultimately won by Brazil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/matches_wallchart/germany_v_brazil/newsid_2067000/2067939.stm|title=Brazil crowned world champions|last=|first=|date=2002-06-30|website=BBC News|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n* [[June 6]] \u2013 An object with an estimated diameter of 10 meters [[2002 Eastern Mediterranean event|collides with Earth]] over the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] and detonates in mid-air.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spacedaily.com/news/deepimpact-02s.html|title=Near-Earth Objects Pose Threat, General Says|last=Bosker|first=A.J.|date=2002-09-17|website=Space Daily|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n* [[June 10]] \u2013 The first direct electronic communication experiment between the nervous systems of two humans is carried out by [[Kevin Warwick]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/nervous-system-hookup-leads-to-telepathic-hand-holding|title=Nervous System Hookup Leads to Telepathic Hand-Holding|last=Giaimo|first=Cara|date=2015-06-10|work=|newspaper=Atlas Obscura|language=en|access-date=2017-01-27|via=}}</ref>\n* [[June 13]] \u2013 Afghanistan changes its official longform name to the [[Transitional Islamic State of Afghanistan]].<ref name=AFG_constitution>[http://president.gov.af/sroot_eng.aspx?id=68 Afghanistan ratified a new constitution on 26 Jan 2004] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127090617/http://president.gov.af/sroot_eng.aspx?id=68 |date=2010-11-27 }}</ref><ref>CIA World Factbook 2003</ref>\n* [[June 24]] \u2013 A passenger train [[Igandu train collision|collides with a freight train]] in [[Dodoma Region]], [[Tanzania]], killing 281 people, making it the worst rail accident in African history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/200-dead-in-tanzania-train-wreck/|title=200 Dead In Tanzania Train Wreck|last=Hancock|first=David|date=2002-06-24|website=CBS News|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n* [[July 1]]\n** The [[Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court|Rome Statute]] comes into force, thereby establishing the [[International Criminal Court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/1970312.stm|title=US renounces world court treaty|last=|first=|date=2002-05-06|website=BBC News|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref>\n** A Russian passenger jet and cargo plane [[2002 \u00dcberlingen mid-air collision|collide]] over the town of [[\u00dcberlingen]], [[Germany]], killing 71 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skyguide.ch:80/en/Dossiers/DossierUeberlingen|title=Information regarding the air accident at \u00dcberlingen on 1 July 2002|date=2009-11-10|access-date=2016-06-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091110144925/http://www.skyguide.ch/en/Dossiers/DossierUeberlingen|archivedate=2009-11-10}}</ref>\n* [[July 9]] \u2013 The [[Organisation of African Unity]] is disbanded and replaced by the [[African Union]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2115736.stm|title=African Union replaces dictators' club|date=2002-07-08|newspaper=BBC News|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n* [[July 27]] &ndash; [[Sknyliv air show disaster]]: 77 people are killed and 543 injured when a fighter jet crashes into spectators during an aerobatics presentation at Sknyliv airfield near Lviv, Ukraine. It is the deadliest air show accident in history.\n\n===August===\n* [[August 26]] \u2013 [[Earth Summit 2002]] begins in [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]], aimed at discussing [[sustainable development]] by the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalissues.org/article/366/world-summit-on-sustainable-development|title=World Summit on Sustainable Development|last=Shah|first=Anup|date=2002-09-07|website=Global Issues|publisher=|language=en-us|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref>\n\n* [[August 27]] - Educational children\u2019s website [[Starfall (website)|Starfall]] is founded.\n\n===September===\n* [[September 10]] \u2013 Switzerland joins the [[United Nations]] as the 190th member state after rejecting a place in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/press/en/2002/GA10041.doc.htm|title=With Admission of Switzerland, United Nations Family Now Numbers 190 Member States|last=|first=|date=2002-09-10|website=United Nations|publisher=|language=en|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref>\n* [[September 19]] \u2013 General [[Robert Gu\u00e9\u00ef]] leads an army mutiny in an attempt to overthrow [[Ivory Coast]] President [[Laurent Gbagbo]], resulting in [[First Ivorian Civil War|civil war]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/ivory-coast-turmoil-in-a-troubled-country-1.1007287|title=Ivory Coast: Turmoil in a troubled country|newspaper=CBC News|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref>\n* [[September 25]] \u2013 The [[2002 Vitim event|Vitim event]], a possible [[bolide]] impact, occurs in [[Irkutsk Oblast]], Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2009/09/0925vitim-meteorite/|title=Mysterious Meteorite Dazzles Siberia|last=Alfred|first=Randy|date=2009-09-25|website=Wired|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n* [[September 26]] \u2013 The [[Senegal]]ese passenger ferry [[MV Le Joola|MV ''Le Joola'']] capsizes in a storm off the coast of [[the Gambia]], killing 1,863 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/a-13-2008-09-26-voa39/400523.html|title=Senegal Marks Anniversary of Ferry Disaster Amid Court Cases|last=|first=|date=2009-11-01|website=Voice of America|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n* [[September 27]] \u2013 [[East Timor]] is admitted to the [[United Nations]] as the 191st member state;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/press/en/2002/ga10069.doc.htm|title=Unanimous Assembly Decision Makes 191st United Nations Member State|last=|first=|date=|website=United Nations|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref> it also changes its official longform name from \"Democratic Republic of East Timor\" to \"Democratic Republic of Timor-Leste\".\n\n===October===\n* [[October 12]] \u2013 [[Jemaah Islamiyah]] militants [[2002 Bali bombings|detonate multiple bombs]] in two nightclubs in [[Kuta]], [[Indonesia]], killing 202 people and injuring over 300 in the worst terrorist act in Indonesia's history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/2778923.stm|title=Bali death toll set at 202|last=|first=|date=2003-02-19|work=|newspaper=BBC News|access-date=2016-06-04|via=}}</ref>\n* [[October 23]]\u2013[[October 25|25]] \u2013 [[Chechnya|Chechen]] rebels take control of the ''[[Nord-Ost]]'' theatre in [[Moscow]] and [[Moscow theater hostage crisis|hold the audience hostage]]. At least 170 people are killed following a Russian attempt to subdue the militants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/oct/24/russia.chechnya|title=Chechen gunmen storm Moscow theatre|last=Steele|first=Nick Paton Walsh Jonathan|date=2002-10-23|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* November \u2013 [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome]] (SARS) [[epidemic]] begins in [[Guangdong]] Province of [[China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/csr/sars/country/table2004_04_21/en/index.html|title=Summary of probable SARS cases with onset of illness from 1 November 2002 to 31 July 2003|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|year=2004|accessdate=2011-06-24|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110624025825/http://www.who.int/csr/sars/country/table2004_04_21/en/index.html|archivedate=2011-06-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[November 7]] \u2013 A [[2002 Gibraltar sovereignty referendum|sovereignty referendum]] is held in [[Gibraltar]]. The people reject Spanish sovereignty.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/11/08/world/gibraltar-rejects-power-sharing-between-britain-and-spain.html|title=Gibraltar Rejects Power-Sharing Between Britain and Spain|last=Daly|first=Emma|date=2002-11-08|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n* [[November 8]] \u2013 The [[United Nations Security Council]] unanimously adopts [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1441|Resolution 1441]], forcing [[Ba'athist Iraq|Iraq]] to either [[Iraq disarmament crisis|disarm or face]] \"serious consequences\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/10/30/world/meast/iraq-weapons-inspections-fast-facts/index.html|title=Iraq Weapons Inspections Fast Facts|last=|first=|date=2016-03-04|website=CNN|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref> Iraq agrees to the terms of the resolution on November 13.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[November 19]] \u2013 [[Prestige oil spill|''Prestige'' oil spill]]: Greek oil tanker {{MV|Prestige}} splits in half off the coast of [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] after spilling an estimated 17.8M US gallons (420,000 bbl) in the worst environmental disaster in the history of the [[Iberian Peninsula]].\n* [[November 25]] \u2013 U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] signs the [[Homeland Security Act]] into law, establishing the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]], in the largest U.S. government reorganization since the creation of the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] in [[1947]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/2512891.stm|title=Bush signs landmark security act|date=2002-11-25|website=BBC News|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref> Following a several month-long transitional period, it commences operations the following year.\n* [[November 28]] \u2013 [[2002 Mombasa attacks]]: Suicide bombers blow up an Israeli-owned hotel in [[Mombasa]], Kenya, but their colleagues failed in their attempt to bring down an [[Arkia Israel Airlines]] charter flight with surface-to-air-missiles.\n\n===December===\n* [[December 23]] \u2013 A U.S. [[General Atomics MQ-1 Predator#Iraq|MQ-1 Predator]] is shot down by an Iraqi [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-25|MiG-25]] in the first combat engagement between a drone and conventional aircraft.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/dec/23/iraq.marktran|title=Iraqi fighters shot down drone, says US|last=Tran|first=Mark|date=2002-12-23|last2=agencies|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref>\n\n==Births==\n<!--  Please do not add yourself, non-notable people, fictional characters, or people without Wikipedia articles to this list. No red links, please. -->\n===January===\n* [[January 14]] &ndash; [[Karina Kovaliova]], Belarusian model\n* [[January 17]] &ndash; [[Samuel (singer)|Samuel]], American-South Korean singer\n* [[January 25]] &ndash; [[Lil Mosey]], American rapper\n\n===February===\n* [[February 4]] &ndash; [[Graham Verchere]], Canadian actor\n* [[February 5]] &ndash; [[Davis Cleveland]], American actor\n* [[February 13]] &ndash; [[Sophia Lillis]], American actress\n\n===March===\n* [[March 16]] &ndash; [[Isabelle Allen]], English actress\n\n===April===\n<!--[[File:Skai Jackson 2011.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Skai Jackson]]]]-->\n[[File:Sadie Sink by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Sadie Sink]]]]\n* [[April 1]] &ndash; [[Don George]],Indian\n* [[April 4]] &ndash; [[Daniel Grassl]], Italian skater\n* [[April 8]] &ndash; [[Skai Jackson]], American actress\n* [[April 16]] &ndash; [[Sadie Sink]], American actress\n\n===May===\n* [[May 18]] &ndash; [[Alina Zagitova]], Russian figure skater\n\n===June===\n* [[June 2]] &ndash; [[Madison Hu]], American actress\n* [[June 25]] &ndash; [[Mason Vale Cotton]], American actor\n\n===July===\n* [[July 21]] &ndash; [[Rika Kihira]], Japanese figure skater\n* [[July 22]] &ndash; [[Prince Felix of Denmark]]\n* [[July 24]] &ndash; [[Benjamin Flores Jr.]], American actor and rapper\n\n===August===\n* [[August 1]] &ndash; [[Oona Laurence]], American actress\n* [[August 19]] &ndash; [[Brighton Sharbino]], American actress\n* [[August 26]] &ndash; [[Lil Tecca]], American rapper\n\n===September===\n<!--[[File:Asher Angel by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Asher Angel]]]]-->\n[[File:Jenna Ortega on Stuck in the Middle.png|thumb|120px|right|[[Jenna Ortega]]]]\n[[File:Maddie Ziegler May 2015-adj.jpg|thumb|120px|right|[[Maddie Ziegler]]]]\n* [[September 6]] &ndash; [[Asher Ange